INSERT INTO public.materials (course_id, title, type, link, pages, content_text) VALUES

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 1: Fundamentals of Data Science - Understanding Data',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_1_Fundamentals_of_Data_Science.pdf',
 17,
 'Lecture 1: Fundamentals of Data Science. Topics: Introduction to Data, Why Data Matters, Data Classification, Real-World Applications. What is Data? Data refers to raw, unorganized facts and figures that represent basic elements of information. Characteristics: Discrete and unorganized, Lacks context, Quantitative or qualitative, Observations or measurements. Data vs Information vs Knowledge vs Wisdom (DIKW Pyramid): Data = Raw unprocessed facts; Information = Organized data with meaning; Knowledge = Patterns and context; Wisdom = Understanding principles. Example: Data: 72, rainy, Seattle → Information: The temperature in Seattle is 72F and rainy → Knowledge: Seattle has frequent winter rain → Wisdom: Pack a raincoat for November visit. The Data Revolution: Data as the New Oil (must be extracted and refined, raw data has little value, powers industries) vs Data as the New Soil (medium for innovation, nurtures business growth). Data Impact Across Industries: Business (personalized marketing, supply chain, customer insights), Scientific Research (climate, astronomy, genomics), Healthcare (predictive diagnostics, drug discovery, epidemiology), Social Impact (urban planning, education, public safety). Three Fundamental Data Types: Structured (20% of data, tables/rows/columns, fixed schema, RDBMS, SQL databases, Excel), Semi-structured (10-15%, tags/markers but no rigid structure, JSON/XML/CSV, NoSQL, schema-on-read, self-describing), Unstructured (80%, no schema, complex, data lakes/cloud storage, emails/documents/images/videos/audio/social media, analyzed with ML/NLP/Computer Vision/Deep Learning). Data Type Comparison: Structured=High organization, Fixed schema, Easy SQL analysis, RDBMS storage; Semi-structured=Medium organization, Flexible schema, Moderate analysis, NoSQL; Unstructured=No organization, No schema, Complex AI/ML analysis, Data Lakes. Healthcare Data Example: Structured=Patient demographics/Lab results/Billing codes; Semi-structured=Medical device data/Survey responses; Unstructured=Clinical notes/Medical images/Voice recordings. E-commerce Data Example: Structured=Product catalogs/Order histories/Inventory; Semi-structured=Product reviews/Clickstream/API responses; Unstructured=Product images/Chat logs/Social media. The Data Scientist Mindset: Data is raw material for insights, Context transforms data into value, Classification determines tool selection, Most valuable data starts unstructured, Goal is to transform data into actionable wisdom. Always start by understanding data nature and structure before choosing analysis methods.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 2: Data Science - From Concepts to Implementation',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_2_From_Concepts_to_Implementation.pdf',
 23,
 'Lecture 2: Data Science From Concepts to Implementation. What is Data Science? Definition: Data Science combines scientific methods, processes, algorithms, and systems to extract knowledge and insights from structured and unstructured data. Core Components: Computer Science, Statistics, Domain Knowledge (The Data Science Trinity). Key Objectives: Descriptive Analytics, Diagnostic Analytics, Predictive Analytics, Prescriptive Analytics. The Data Science Ecosystem: Computer Science (Algorithms, Distributed Computing, Database Management), Mathematics (Statistics, Probability Theory, Linear Algebra, Statistical Inference), Domain Expertise (Industry Knowledge, Problem Context). Key Insight: Without domain knowledge, you are just analyzing numbers without meaning. CRISP-DM Methodology (Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining): Phase 1 Business Understanding (What problem? Who are stakeholders? How measure success? Common pitfalls: vague problem statements, unclear metrics, missing alignment), Phase 2 Data Understanding (Data Collection, Initial Exploration, Quality Assessment, Pattern Identification, Tools: Pandas Profiling, SweetViz), Phase 3 Data Preparation (Handle missing values, Remove duplicates, Correct inconsistencies, Feature Engineering, Normalization/Standardization/One-Hot Encoding/Text Vectorization), Phase 4 Modeling (Classification: Logistic Regression/Random Forest for spam detection; Regression: Linear Regression/Decision Trees for price prediction; Clustering: K-Means/DBSCAN for customer segmentation; Dimensionality Reduction: PCA/t-SNE. Model Training: Train-Test Split 70-30 or 80-20, Hyperparameter Tuning, Cross-validation), Phase 5 Evaluation (Classification Metrics: Accuracy=(TP+TN)/Total, Precision=TP/(TP+FP), Recall=TP/(TP+FN), F1-Score=harmonic mean; Regression Metrics: MAE, RMSE, R-squared; Business Validation), Phase 6 Deployment (Batch Processing, Real-time API, Embedded Models, Model Serving with Flask). Machine Learning Types: Supervised Learning (labeled data, predicts known outcomes, Classification/Regression), Unsupervised Learning (unlabeled data, discovers hidden patterns, Clustering/Association), Reinforcement Learning (learns through interaction, maximizes reward, Game AI/Robotics). Supervised Deep Dive: Classification with RandomForestClassifier, Common algorithms: Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, SVM, Neural Networks. Unsupervised Deep Dive: K-Means clustering for customer segmentation, Applications: anomaly detection, market basket analysis, document clustering. Data Science Toolbox: Python (pandas, numpy, sklearn, tensorflow, matplotlib, seaborn), Jupyter Notebooks, VS Code, Google Colab. Big Data Technologies: Apache Spark, Hadoop, Dask, Kafka; Cloud: AWS SageMaker, Google Cloud AI, Azure ML. Model Evaluation: Cross-Validation (5-fold), ROC Curve, Confusion Matrix, AUC. Feature Engineering: Numerical (Binning, Log transforms, Polynomial, Interaction terms), Categorical (One-Hot, Label, Target, Frequency encoding), Text (Bag-of-Words, TF-IDF, Word Embeddings), Time Series (Lag features, Rolling statistics, Seasonal decomposition). Real-World Applications: Healthcare (disease prediction, medical image analysis), E-commerce (recommendation systems, price optimization), Finance (fraud detection, algorithmic trading, credit scoring), Manufacturing (predictive maintenance, quality control). Common Challenges: Data Quality→robust cleaning; Model Performance→cross-validation/regularization/ensembles; Interpretability→SHAP/LIME; Deployment→MLOps; Ethics→fairness metrics. Future Trends: AutoML, Explainable AI, MLOps, Federated Learning, AI Ethics. Key Takeaways: Start with business problem, Data quality is paramount, Iterate and validate, Think about deployment early, Communicate results effectively.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 3: Knowledge Extraction from Big Data (Detailed Notes)',
 'notes',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_3_Knowledge_Extraction_Big_Data_Notes.pdf',
 11,
 'Lecture 3: Comprehensive Framework for Knowledge Extraction from Big Data. The Big Data Revolution: paradigm shift from static to dynamic massive data streams, driven by digitization of IoT, social media, genomics. The 4 Vs of Big Data: 1. Volume (TB to PB+ scale, distributed file systems like HDFS, parallel processing like Spark), 2. Velocity (real-time data generation/processing, stream processing with Kafka/Flink, batch processing insufficient for fraud detection/dynamic pricing), 3. Variety (structured/semi-structured/unstructured formats, requires NLP and computer vision), 4. Veracity (noise/bias/trustworthiness, data governance and preprocessing critical). Additional Vs: Value, Variability, Visualization. The Knowledge Pyramid (DIKW): Data→Information→Knowledge→Wisdom. Knowledge extraction moves up pyramid through analytical processes. CRISP-DM Framework: 1. Business Understanding (define problem, convert to data mining goal, establish success criteria), 2. Data Understanding (acquire data, explore, descriptive statistics, identify quality issues), 3. Data Preparation (most time-consuming, cleaning/feature engineering/integration), 4. Modeling (select algorithms, build models, tune parameters, cross-validation), 5. Evaluation (assess against business criteria, review process), 6. Deployment (integrate into business, monitoring/maintenance). Alternative Methodologies: KDD Process (academic, discovery emphasis), SEMMA (SAS Institute, tool-centric), TDSP (Microsoft, agile/DevOps/MLOps). Core Extraction Techniques: Statistical Methods (descriptive, inferential, time series, multivariate), Machine Learning (Supervised: Classification/Regression/Ensembles; Unsupervised: Clustering/Association/Dimensionality Reduction; Semi-supervised/Self-supervised; Deep Learning: CNNs/RNNs/Transformers/GANs), Advanced Techniques (Graph Analytics with community detection/centrality/link prediction, NLP with topic modeling/sentiment analysis/NER, Anomaly Detection with Z-scores/Isolation Forest/autoencoders, Network Analysis). Big Data Processing Architectures: Lambda (Batch+Speed+Serving layers, robust but complex), Kappa (stream-only, simpler, reprocessing from log), Data Lake (raw storage, schema-on-read, risk of data swamp, Lakehouse solutions). Tools and Platforms: Python (NumPy/Pandas/SciPy/Scikit-learn/TensorFlow/PyTorch), R (Tidyverse/caret/Shiny), SQL variants (HiveQL/Spark SQL/Presto), Scala/Java (Spark native, Weka/Deeplearning4j). Big Data Frameworks: Batch (Hadoop MapReduce, Apache Spark), Stream (Kafka, Flink, Storm), Cloud Platforms (AWS/GCP/Azure comparison). Implementation Considerations: Scalability (horizontal/vertical), Performance (data locality, in-memory, columnar), Data Governance (lineage, cataloging, quality), Security (encryption, RBAC, differential privacy). Emerging Trends: Serverless, AutoML, real-time analytics, Unified batch/stream (Apache Beam), Data Mesh/Fabric/Lakehouse, Causal inference, Explainable AI, GNNs, Multimodal learning. Best Practices: Start with business problem, cross-functional teams, iterative development, data quality first, plan for scalability. Pitfalls: Technology-first approach, ignoring data quality, neglecting model maintenance, overlooking ethics.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 3: Knowledge Extraction from Big Data (Slides)',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_3_Knowledge_Extraction_Big_Data_Slides.pdf',
 14,
 'Lecture 3 Slides: Knowledge Extraction from Big Data. Agenda: Big Data Revolution, Knowledge Extraction Methodology (CRISP-DM), Core Techniques (Stats/ML/NLP), Big Data Architectures (Lambda/Kappa/Data Lake), Tools and Ecosystem, Implementation Considerations, Emerging Trends, Best Practices and Case Studies. The 4 Vs: Volume (TB to PB+), Velocity (real-time streams), Variety (structured to unstructured), Veracity (data quality and trust). Knowledge Pyramid (DIKW): Data→Information→Knowledge→Wisdom, Extraction = moving up the pyramid via analysis. CRISP-DM Framework: 6 phases - Business Understanding, Data Understanding, Data Preparation, Modeling, Evaluation, Deployment. Alternatives: KDD, SEMMA, TDSP. Core Extraction Techniques: Statistical Methods (descriptive/inferential/time series/multivariate), Machine Learning (Supervised: Classification/Regression/Ensembles; Unsupervised: Clustering/Association/Dimensionality Reduction; Deep Learning: CNNs/RNNs/Transformers/GANs), Advanced (Graph Analytics, NLP, Anomaly Detection, Network Analysis). Big Data Architectures: Lambda (Batch+Speed+Serving, robust but complex), Kappa (Stream-only, simpler, reprocessing from log), Data Lake (Raw storage, schema-on-read, risk: data swamp), Lakehouse solutions. Tools: Python/R/SQL/Scala-Java, Frameworks: Hadoop/Spark/Flink/Kafka, Cloud: AWS/GCP/Azure, Specialized: Airflow/MLflow/Tableau/Jupyter. Implementation: Scalability, Performance, Data Governance, Security and Privacy. Emerging Trends: Serverless, AutoML, real-time, Apache Beam, Data Mesh/Fabric/Lakehouse, Causal inference, Explainable AI, GNNs. Case Studies: Netflix recommendation, Uber surge pricing, Airbnb fraud detection, Walmart supply chain, Healthcare predictive analytics.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 4: Problem Formulation in Data Science',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_4_Problem_Formulation.pdf',
 17,
 'Lecture 4: Problem Formulation in Data Science. Contents: Understanding the Domain Problem, Problem Statement Formulation, Hypothesis Formulation, The Integrated Process, Tools and Templates. Key Principle: No amount of sophisticated analytics can compensate for a poorly understood problem. What is a Domain Problem? A real-world challenge within a specific field that: Has measurable impact, Can be addressed through data-driven insights, Exists within constraints (technical, ethical, regulatory, budgetary). Examples: Healthcare (Reduce patient readmission rates by 15% within 12 months), Retail (Increase customer lifetime value by identifying high-value segments), Manufacturing (Predict equipment failure to reduce downtime). The Critical First Step: Problem Understanding using Who (identify stakeholders), What (define problem clearly), Why (quantify impact), Where (determine context), When (identify temporal patterns), How (understand current solutions). SMART Framework for Problem Statements: Specific (clear and unambiguous), Measurable (quantifiable success criteria), Achievable (realistic given constraints), Relevant (aligns with business objectives), Time-bound (includes timeframe). Problem Statement Template: In the context of [DOMAIN], we are facing [SPECIFIC PROBLEM] which affects [STAKEHOLDERS] resulting in [QUANTIFIED IMPACT]. A successful solution would [DESIRED OUTCOME] measured by [SUCCESS METRICS] within [TIMEFRAME]. Example Transformations: Poor: We need to improve sales → Improved: Q3 sales in Northeast decreased by 18% due to churn in 25-35 age group. Poor: Make our website better → Improved: Mobile users have 65% higher bounce rate and 40% shorter sessions. Types of Hypotheses: Research (Customer satisfaction affects retention rates), Statistical (H0: No correlation; H1: Higher satisfaction correlates with higher retention), Machine Learning (Feature X improves prediction accuracy by at least 5%). Hypothesis Development Framework: Observation→Question→Literature Review→Hypothesis Formulation. Hypothesis Prioritization using ICE Scoring: Impact (Expected improvement over baseline), Confidence (Evidence strength), Ease (Feasibility and cost of testing). Data Science Process Flow: 1. Domain Understanding, 2. Problem Statement Formulation, 3. Hypothesis Generation, 4. Data Requirements, 5. Experimental Design, 6. Execution and Validation. Case Study E-commerce: Problem Statement about conversion rate 40% below industry average for mobile users, Hypotheses: mobile checkout too many steps, slow page load times, difficulty with discount codes. Hypothesis Testing Matrix with test design, data required, success criteria. Key Takeaways: Domain understanding comes first, Problem statements should be SMART, Hypotheses must be testable and falsifiable, Iterate and refine continuously, Document assumptions and decisions. The most important step in data science is not building models—its asking the right questions.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 5: The Data Phase - Understanding and Preparation',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_5_Data_Phase_Understanding_Preparation.pdf',
 22,
 'Lecture 5: The Data Phase in Data Science: Understanding and Preparation. Agenda: CRISP-DM Framework, Data Understanding Phase, Data Preparation Phase, Best Practices, Case Study: Customer Churn Prediction, Summary. Key Insight: Data Phase (Understanding + Preparation) consumes 60-80% of project time. Success here directly determines modeling efficacy. Objectives of Data Understanding: Gain familiarity with data, Identify data quality issues, Form initial hypotheses, Detect interesting subsets. Core Activities in Data Understanding: 1. Data Collection, 2. Data Description, 3. Data Exploration, 4. Data Quality Assessment. Data Collection Strategies: Proactive vs Retrospective, Sampling methods: Random, Stratified, Systematic, Cluster. Data Exploration Techniques: Univariate (Histograms, Box plots, Normality tests), Bivariate (Scatter plots, Correlation, Cross-tabs), Multivariate (PCA, Cluster analysis, Association rules). Data Quality Assessment Framework: Completeness (Missing value percentage, Pattern analysis), Consistency (Cross-validation, Logical checks), Accuracy (Validation against standards), Timeliness (Freshness, Update frequency), Uniqueness (Duplicate identification). Objectives of Data Preparation: Transform raw data into analysis-ready format, Address data quality issues, Create derived variables, Structure data for algorithms. Core Activities in Data Preparation: 1. Data Selection, 2. Data Cleaning, 3. Data Construction, 4. Data Integration, 5. Data Formatting. Handling Missing Data: Deletion (Listwise, Pairwise), Imputation (Mean/Median/Mode, Regression: x_hat = beta0 + beta1*x1 + ... + betak*xk, K-Nearest Neighbors, Multiple Imputation). Data Scaling and Normalization: Min-Max Scaling: x_prime = (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)), Z-score Standardization: x_prime = (x - mu) / sigma, Robust Scaling (using median and IQR). Encoding Categorical Variables: One-hot encoding, Label encoding (for ordinal data), Target encoding, Frequency encoding. Tool Agnostic Principles: Reproducibility (Script all transformations, Version control, Documentation). Scalability Considerations: Incremental processing, Parallel/distributed computing (Spark), Efficient memory management. Quality Assurance: Automated validation checks, Backward traceability, Statistical and business validation. Case Study: Customer Churn Prediction - Data Understanding: 50,000 customers, 85 features, 15% churn rate, 8% missing in support data. Data Preparation Outcome: 112 features, 98% completeness, Fully documented pipeline. Key Takeaways: Data phase is foundational for model performance, Understanding precedes preparation, Documentation is non-negotiable, Iteration is expected, Business context guides technical decisions.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 7: CRISP-DM Framework - Model Build Phase',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_7_CRISP_DM_Model_Build_Phase.pdf',
 18,
 'Lecture 7: CRISP-DM Framework Model Build Phase. Agenda: Introduction to Model Build Phase, Model Selection Strategy, Modeling Workflow, Overfitting Prevention, Model Assessment Metrics, Best Practices, Tools and Deliverables, Transition to Evaluation. Core Objectives: Select appropriate modeling techniques, Build and calibrate models, Optimize model performance, Address business objectives. Key Principles: Iterative experimentation, Technique-agnostic approach, Comprehensive documentation, Business alignment. Matching Problems with Techniques: Classification (Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forest, SVM, Neural Networks - consider class imbalance, interpretability), Regression (Linear Regression, Decision Trees, Gradient Boosting, Neural Networks - consider non-linearity, outlier sensitivity), Clustering (K-Means, DBSCAN, Hierarchical - consider cluster count, scalability), Time Series (ARIMA, Prophet, LSTM - consider seasonality, trend). Selection Criteria Matrix: Technical (Accuracy requirements, Training time, Prediction speed, Data volume, Feature types), Business (Interpretability, Deployment environment, Maintenance, Regulatory compliance, Stakeholder preferences). Golden Rule: Start simple then increase complexity. 7-Step Modeling Process: 1. Select Techniques, 2. Generate Test Design, 3. Build Initial Models, 4. Preliminary Assessment, 5. Tune Hyperparameters, 6. Validate Models. Cross-Validation Strategies: K-fold (5 or 10), Stratified K-fold, Time-series CV, Hold-out validation. Hyperparameter Tuning Methods: Grid Search, Random Search, Bayesian Optimization, Evolutionary Algorithms. The Bias-Variance Tradeoff: Total Error = Bias² + Variance + Irreducible Error. Prevention Strategies: Regularization (L1/L2, Dropout, Early Stopping), Validation (Proper data splits, Cross-validation, Out-of-time validation), Simplicity (Occams Razor, Baseline models, Feature selection). Key Performance Metrics: Classification (Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-Score, AUC-ROC), Regression (MAE, RMSE, R²). Best Practices DO: Start with baseline models, Use version control, Set random seeds, Create pipelines, Monitor training dynamics, Involve domain experts. DONT: Data leakage, Over-optimization, Ignoring baselines, Premature complexity, Metric myopia, Forgetting reproducibility. Iterative Nature: Multiple iterations between Data Prep, Modeling, and Evaluation are normal. Tools Stack: Python (scikit-learn, XGBoost/LightGBM, TensorFlow/PyTorch), R (caret/mlr3, tidymodels), AutoML (H2O, TPOT, Auto-sklearn), Experiment Tracking (MLflow, Weights and Biases, TensorBoard, DVC). Key Deliverables: Technical (Trained model files, Model documentation/cards, Performance reports, Feature importance, Error analysis, Reproducible code), Decision (Model comparison matrix, Trade-off analysis, Risk assessment, Deployment readiness report). Readiness Checklist: Technical (Models exceed baseline, Documentation, Test set evaluation, Error analysis, Computational specs), Business (Metrics projected, Stakeholders briefed, Trade-offs analyzed, Risks identified). Success = Models that address business problems within constraints, NOT model complexity or novel algorithms.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lecture 8: Data Modeling Algorithms',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_8_Data_Modeling_Algorithms.pdf',
 33,
 'Lecture 8: DTS 201 Some Data Modeling Algorithms. Algorithm Selection Framework: Problem Type (Supervised/Unsupervised/Semi-supervised/Reinforcement), Target Variable (Continuous/Discrete/Ordinal/No target), Feature Characteristics (Numerical/Categorical/Text/Image/Sequence), Data Volume, Interpretability Need, Resource Constraints. 1. Linear Regression: Y = beta0 + beta1*X1 + ... + betaN*XN + epsilon. Strengths: Most interpretable, Closed-form solution, Low variance. Weaknesses: Fails with non-linearity, Sensitive to outliers, Multicollinearity issues. 2. Ridge and Lasso Regression: Ridge (L2): min(Y-Y_hat)² + lambda*sum(betaj²). Lasso (L1): min(Y-Y_hat)² + lambda*sum(|betaj|). Elastic Net combines both. Ridge handles multicollinearity, Lasso does feature selection. 3. Logistic Regression: P(Y=1|X) = 1/(1+e^-(beta0+beta1*X1+...)). Well-calibrated probabilities, Fast, Interpretable coefficients. Weaknesses: Linear decision boundary. 4. K-Nearest Neighbors: Store training data, Compute distances, Select K closest, Majority vote/average. No training phase, Complex decision boundaries. Weaknesses: Slow prediction O(n), Curse of dimensionality. 5. Support Vector Machine: Kernel Trick (Linear, Polynomial, RBF). Effective in high dimensions, Memory efficient. Weaknesses: Poor with overlapping classes, O(n²) to O(n³) training. 6. Decision Tree (CART): Split Criteria: Gini=1-sum(pi²), Entropy=-sum(pi*log2(pi)), MSE for regression. Highly interpretable, No scaling needed. Weaknesses: High variance, Prone to overfitting. 7. Random Forest: Bootstrap aggregating (bagging), Random feature selection, OOB error. High accuracy, Resistant to overfitting, Feature importance. Weaknesses: Black box, Large memory. 8. Gradient Boosting (XGBoost/LightGBM/CatBoost): Sequential Learning Fm(x) = Fm-1(x) + eta*hm(x). State-of-the-art for tabular data, Handles missing values. Weaknesses: Many hyperparameters. 9. Naive Bayes: P(C|F) = P(C)*product(P(F|C))/P(F). Extremely fast, Works with high dimensions. Weaknesses: Independence assumption. 10. Neural Networks: z=sum(wi*xi)+b, a=sigma(z). CNN for images, RNN/LSTM for sequences, Transformer for NLP. Universal approximators. Weaknesses: Needs large data, Black box. 11. K-Means: Objective min sum(||x-mu_c||²). Initialize K centroids, Assign points, Update centroids, Repeat. Simple, scalable O(n). Weaknesses: Must specify K, Spherical clusters only. 12. Hierarchical Clustering: Agglomerative (bottom-up) and Divisive (top-down). Linkage: Single/Complete/Average/Ward. No need to specify K, Dendrogram visualization. Weaknesses: O(n³) complexity. 13. DBSCAN: Density-based. Core (>=MinPts within epsilon), Border, Noise. Arbitrary shapes, Robust to outliers. Weaknesses: Sensitive to epsilon. 14. PCA: Standardize→Covariance matrix→Eigendecomposition→Project to top k components. Removes multicollinearity, Noise reduction. Weaknesses: Linear only. 15. t-SNE: Non-linear visualization, Convert distances to probabilities, Student-t distribution, Minimize KL divergence. 16. Apriori Algorithm: Support=P(Itemset), Confidence=P(Y|X), Lift=P(X∪Y)/(P(X)*P(Y)). 17. FP-Growth: FP-tree construction (2 scans), Much faster than Apriori. 18. ARIMA: AR(p)+I(d)+MA(q), Seasonal ARIMA(p,d,q)(P,D,Q)m. 19. LSTM: Gates: forget/input/output. Long-term dependencies, Variable-length sequences. 20. Isolation Forest: Anomalies are few and different, easier to isolate. s(x,n) = 2^(-E(h(x))/c(n)). Algorithm Selection by Target Type table and Trade-offs table included. Case Studies: Customer Churn (XGBoost winner), Fraud Detection (XGBoost balance), Image Classification (Fine-tuned ResNet50), Market Basket (FP-Growth 18x faster), Customer Segmentation (DBSCAN winner).'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lectures 9 & 10: CRISP-DM Evaluation and Deployment (Notes)',
 'notes',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_9_10_Evaluation_Deployment_Notes.pdf',
 8,
 'Lectures 9 and 10: CRISP-DM Phases 5 and 6 - Evaluation and Deployment. Phase 5: Evaluation. Objective: Assess model(s) from both technical and business perspectives. Core question: Does the model meet the business objectives from Phase 1? 5.1 Evaluate Results: Review Business Success Criteria (revisit Phase 1 goals, analyze business impact not just statistical metrics, use A/B tests or champion/challenger analysis). Apply Technical Performance Metrics: Classification (Confusion Matrix: TP/TN/FP/FN, Accuracy=(TP+TN)/(TP+TN+FP+FN), Precision=TP/(TP+FP) critical when FP cost is high, Recall=TP/(TP+FN) critical when FN cost is high, F1-Score=2*Precision*Recall/(Precision+Recall), AUC-ROC measures discrimination, Log-Loss measures prediction certainty), Regression (MAE=1/n*sum|yi-y_hat_i|, MSE=1/n*sum(yi-y_hat_i)², RMSE=sqrt(MSE), R-Squared=1-sum(yi-y_hat_i)²/sum(yi-y_bar)²). Assess Process and Interpret Model: Is model logically sound? Feature Importance, SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations), LIME (Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) for trust and insights. 5.2 Review Process: Process Review (systematic review, were steps overlooked?). Determine Next Steps: 1. Proceed to Deployment (meets objectives), 2. Iterate (most common, go back to Modeling/Data Preparation), 3. Initiate New Project (different problem found), 4. End Project (not viable). Phase 6: Deployment. Objective: Put model and insights into production. Key principle: customer uses results, not modeling work. 6.1 Plan Deployment: Simple/Static (one-off report/dashboard, Tableau/Power BI/Looker), Batch/Offline (runs periodically, Python/R with Airflow/AWS Glue, output in SQL/Snowflake/BigQuery), Real-time/Online (API service, serialized with Pickle/Joblib/ONNX/PMML, served via Flask/FastAPI/Django, containerized with Docker/Kubernetes, Cloud: AWS SageMaker/Azure ML/Google AI Platform). 6.2 Monitoring and Maintenance: Models are NOT fire and forget. Model drift/concept drift causes degradation. Performance Tracking (pipeline for ground-truth collection), Data and Concept Drift Detection (Evidently AI, WhyLabs, SageMaker Model Monitor), Maintenance Schedule (monthly/quarterly), CI/CD for ML (MLOps) for automated model updates. 6.3 Produce Final Report: Project Summary, Final Results with BI visualizations, Process Explanation (non-technical), Technical Documentation (appendix for engineers), Conclusions and Recommendations. 6.4 Review Project: Post-mortem, Document Lessons Learned, Create knowledge base, Final presentation to stakeholders. Conclusion: CRISP-DM is cyclical - Evaluation leads back to Modeling, Deployment reveals new data needs, Lessons inform next project. Mastering these phases separates a data scientist from a data science professional.'),

('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4',
 'Lectures 9 & 10: CRISP-DM Evaluation and Deployment (Slides)',
 'slides',
 '/materials/dts201/Lecture_9_10_Evaluation_Deployment_Slides.pdf',
 22,
 'Lectures 9 and 10 Slides: CRISP-DM Evaluation and Deployment. Recall first four phases: Business Understanding, Data Understanding, Data Preparation, Modeling. The Critical Gap: A model that performs well in a lab is of no value if it doesnt solve the business problem or never gets used. Phase 5 Evaluation Objective: Assess from business perspective, not just technical. 5.1 Evaluate Results - Business Criteria: Revisit Phase 1 goals, Use A/B tests or Champion/Challenger. Technical Metrics for Classification: Confusion Matrix (TP/TN/FP/FN), Accuracy, Precision (Low FP critical), Recall (Low FN critical), F1-Score, AUC-ROC and Log-Loss. Technical Metrics for Regression: MAE (average error), MSE (penalizes large errors), RMSE (error in original units), R-Squared (variance explained). Model Interpretation: Feature Importance, SHAP, LIME - build trust. 5.2 Review Process and Next Steps: Process Review, Determine: Proceed/Iterate(most common)/New Project/End. Phase 6 Deployment Objective: Put model into production. Customer uses results not modeling work. 6.1 Deployment Methods: Simple/Static (Tableau, Power BI, Looker), Batch/Offline (Airflow, AWS Glue, Snowflake, BigQuery), Real-time/Online API (Pickle/Joblib/ONNX/PMML, Flask/FastAPI/Django, Docker/Kubernetes, SageMaker/Azure ML/Google AI Platform). 6.1 Monitoring: Models degrade due to Model Drift. 6.2 Plan Monitoring: Performance Tracking, Drift Detection (Evidently AI, WhyLabs), Maintenance Schedule, CI/CD for ML (MLOps). 6.3 Final Report: Project Summary, Results with BI tools, Process Explanation, Technical Documentation, Conclusions and Recommendations. 6.4 Review Project: Post-Mortem, Document Lessons Learned. Conclusion: CRISP-DM is cyclical. Key Takeaways: 1. Evaluation is about business value not just technical metrics, 2. Use the right technical metrics, 3. Deployment can be static/batch/real-time, 4. Monitoring is essential to combat model drift, 5. Always document and review.');